{
  "format": "tiptap/v1",
  "doc": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A vector database does not just store embeddings — it stores vectors alongside a payload of metadata. That metadata is the lever that turns a general-purpose similarity search into a precise retrieval query: \"find the 5 most relevant chunks, but only from documents uploaded in the last 30 days, belonging to this tenant, of type 'policy'\". This document covers how to design metadata schemas, how metadata filtering interacts with approximate nearest-neighbour (ANN) indexes, and when to partition data into separate namespaces or collections instead."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "image",
        "attrs": {
          "src": "data:image/svg+xml;base64,",
          "alt": "Two approaches compared: Approach A (single collection + metadata filter) stores all tenant vectors in one collection with tenant/type metadata, and queries filter at search time — simple but scans all vectors. Approach B (namespace per tenant) keeps each tenant in its own index partition so queries only scan that tenant's vectors — perfect isolation but expensive for cross-tenant queries."
        }
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Metadata Schema Design"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Every chunk you store should carry enough metadata to filter the search, attribute the result to a source, and enable lifecycle management (deletion, re-indexing). Design the payload before you ingest a single chunk."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from dataclasses import dataclass, asdict\nfrom datetime import datetime, timezone\n\n@dataclass\nclass ChunkPayload:\n    # Filtering fields — kept small for index performance\n    tenant_id: str\n    doc_id: str\n    doc_type: str            # 'policy', 'code', 'faq', 'email', ...\n    source: str              # filename or URL\n    language: str = \"en\"\n\n    # Temporal fields — enable recency filtering\n    created_at: str = \"\"    # ISO-8601 string; vector DBs vary on date support\n    updated_at: str = \"\"\n\n    # Positional fields — enable context reconstruction\n    chunk_index: int = 0\n    page_number: int = 0\n    section: str = \"\"\n\n    # Content fields — enable display without DB lookup\n    text_preview: str = \"\"  # first 200 chars; shown in UI before full fetch\n\n    def __post_init__(self):\n        now = datetime.now(timezone.utc).isoformat()\n        if not self.created_at:\n            self.created_at = now\n        if not self.updated_at:\n            self.updated_at = now\n\n    def to_dict(self) -> dict:\n        return asdict(self)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Keep the payload under ~2 KB per chunk. Large payloads (storing full chunk text) are not indexed — they are serialised alongside the vector — but they increase memory usage and slow index scans in systems that load payload alongside the ANN graph."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Metadata Filtering in Practice"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Qdrant"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Qdrant's filter system supports must/should/must_not with range, match, and nested conditions. Filters are applied inside the HNSW graph traversal, not as a post-scan step, so they are efficient even on large collections."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "from qdrant_client import QdrantClient\nfrom qdrant_client.models import Filter, FieldCondition, MatchValue, Range\n\nclient = QdrantClient(url=\"http://qdrant:6333\")\n\ndef search_filtered(\n    query_vector: list[float],\n    tenant_id: str,\n    doc_type: str | None = None,\n    after_date: str | None = None,   # ISO-8601\n    top_k: int = 5,\n) -> list[dict]:\n    must_conditions = [\n        FieldCondition(key=\"tenant_id\", match=MatchValue(value=tenant_id)),\n    ]\n    if doc_type:\n        must_conditions.append(\n            FieldCondition(key=\"doc_type\", match=MatchValue(value=doc_type))\n        )\n    if after_date:\n        must_conditions.append(\n            FieldCondition(key=\"created_at\", range=Range(gte=after_date))\n        )\n\n    hits = client.search(\n        collection_name=\"documents\",\n        query_vector=query_vector,\n        query_filter=Filter(must=must_conditions),\n        limit=top_k,\n        with_payload=True,\n    )\n    return [\n        {\"text\": h.payload[\"text_preview\"], \"source\": h.payload[\"source\"],\n         \"score\": h.score}\n        for h in hits\n    ]\n\n# Usage\nresults = search_filtered(\n    query_vector=embed(\"what is the refund policy?\"),\n    tenant_id=\"acme-corp\",\n    doc_type=\"policy\",\n    after_date=\"2025-01-01T00:00:00Z\",\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "pgvector"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "In pgvector, metadata filtering is just SQL — a WHERE clause before the ORDER BY vector distance. The planner uses available B-Tree or GIN indexes on those columns and then performs the ANN scan within the filtered set."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "sql"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "-- Good: filter columns indexed, vector scan is selective\nSELECT chunk_text, source, 1 - (embedding <=> $1::vector) AS similarity\nFROM   document_chunks\nWHERE  tenant_id = $2          -- BTREE index\n  AND  doc_type  = $3          -- BTREE index\n  AND  created_at >= $4        -- BTREE index\nORDER  BY embedding <=> $1::vector\nLIMIT  5;\n\n-- Partial HNSW index for common filter combinations\nCREATE INDEX ON document_chunks\n    USING hnsw (embedding vector_cosine_ops)\n    WHERE doc_type = 'policy';   -- index only policy docs"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Partial indexes are powerful: if 80% of queries filter on "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "doc_type = 'policy'"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ", a partial HNSW index on that subset is both smaller and faster than an index covering all rows. Build one partial index per high-selectivity filter combination."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pinecone"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Pinecone supports metadata filtering via a filter dict passed alongside the query vector. Filterable fields must be scalar types (string, number, boolean, list of strings) — nested objects are not filterable."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "index = pinecone.Index(\"my-index\")\n\nresults = index.query(\n    vector=query_embedding,\n    top_k=5,\n    filter={\n        \"tenant_id\": {\"$eq\": \"acme-corp\"},\n        \"doc_type\":  {\"$in\": [\"policy\", \"faq\"]},\n        \"created_at\": {\"$gte\": \"2025-01-01\"},\n    },\n    include_metadata=True,\n    namespace=\"prod\",\n)"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Namespace Strategies"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "A namespace (Pinecone) or separate collection (Qdrant/Weaviate) is a fully isolated vector index partition. Vectors in different namespaces never interact — a query against namespace A never touches namespace B's vectors. This is fundamentally different from metadata filtering, which filters within a single shared index."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to use namespaces"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Strict tenant isolation: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If your compliance requirements demand that tenant A's vectors physically never share storage with tenant B's, namespaces are the right tool. Metadata filtering within a shared index relies on the query planner to respect the filter; a namespace enforces isolation structurally."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Performance isolation: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "A tenant with 50M vectors and high QPS can saturate an HNSW graph that other tenants share. Separate namespaces give each tenant their own HNSW graph with no interference."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Easy data lifecycle: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Deleting all vectors for a tenant is a single "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "code"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "delete_namespace()"
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": " call rather than a bulk filtered delete that can take hours."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Pinecone serverless: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Namespaces are free in Pinecone serverless — there is no extra charge for having many namespaces. Use one namespace per tenant as a default."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "When to use metadata filtering instead"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "bulletList",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Cross-filter queries: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If you need to search across all tenants (e.g. an admin feature), a single collection with metadata lets you issue one query. With namespaces you must fan out across all tenants and merge results."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Dynamic filters: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "If the filter combinations are unknown in advance (\"search docs from the last 7 days in any language\"), metadata filtering is more flexible than pre-partitioning into namespaces."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "listItem",
            "content": [
              {
                "type": "paragraph",
                "content": [
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "marks": [
                      {
                        "type": "bold"
                      }
                    ],
                    "text": "Small collections: "
                  },
                  {
                    "type": "text",
                    "text": "Below ~500K vectors per namespace, the HNSW graph is small enough that metadata filtering within a single collection has negligible latency penalty."
                  }
                ]
              }
            ]
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Hierarchical Namespace Design"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "For multi-tenant SaaS with diverse doc types, combine both approaches: namespace per tenant, metadata filter within the namespace for doc type and date:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "def build_namespace(tenant_id: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"One Pinecone namespace per tenant.\"\"\"\n    return f\"tenant_{tenant_id}\"\n\ndef upsert_chunk(index, tenant_id: str, chunk: dict, embedding: list[float]) -> None:\n    index.upsert(\n        vectors=[{\n            \"id\": chunk[\"id\"],\n            \"values\": embedding,\n            \"metadata\": {\n                \"doc_id\":   chunk[\"doc_id\"],\n                \"doc_type\": chunk[\"doc_type\"],\n                \"source\":   chunk[\"source\"],\n                \"created_at\": chunk[\"created_at\"],\n                \"text\":     chunk[\"text\"][:500],  # preview only\n            },\n        }],\n        namespace=build_namespace(tenant_id),\n    )\n\ndef retrieve(\n    index,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    query_vector: list[float],\n    doc_type: str | None = None,\n    top_k: int = 5,\n) -> list[dict]:\n    filter_dict = {}\n    if doc_type:\n        filter_dict[\"doc_type\"] = {\"$eq\": doc_type}\n\n    result = index.query(\n        vector=query_vector,\n        top_k=top_k,\n        filter=filter_dict or None,\n        include_metadata=True,\n        namespace=build_namespace(tenant_id),\n    )\n    return [{\"text\": m.metadata[\"text\"], \"score\": m.score} for m in result.matches]"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Deleting and Updating Documents"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Vector databases are append-optimised. Updating a chunk means deleting the old vector and inserting the new one. Use the "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "code"
              }
            ],
            "text": "doc_id"
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " to find all chunks belonging to a document, then delete and re-ingest:"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "codeBlock",
        "attrs": {
          "language": "python"
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "# Pinecone: delete all chunks for a document\ndef delete_document(index, tenant_id: str, doc_id: str) -> None:\n    # Pinecone serverless supports filter-based delete\n    index.delete(\n        filter={\"doc_id\": {\"$eq\": doc_id}},\n        namespace=build_namespace(tenant_id),\n    )\n\n# Qdrant: delete by payload filter\ndef delete_document_qdrant(client, collection: str, doc_id: str) -> None:\n    from qdrant_client.models import Filter, FieldCondition, MatchValue\n    client.delete(\n        collection_name=collection,\n        points_selector=Filter(\n            must=[FieldCondition(key=\"doc_id\", match=MatchValue(value=doc_id))]\n        ),\n    )\n\n# pgvector: standard SQL DELETE\ndef delete_document_pg(conn, doc_id: str) -> None:\n    with conn, conn.cursor() as cur:\n        cur.execute(\"DELETE FROM document_chunks WHERE doc_id = %s\", (doc_id,))"
          }
        ]
      },
